<code class="hidden_elem" id="u_0_12"><!-- <div class="_5pcb"><h2 class="accessible_elem" id="newsFeedHeading">News Feed</h2><div class="_4-u2 mbm _5jmm _5pat _5v3q _5uun _4-u8" data-ft="&#123;&quot;fbfeed_location&quot;:5&#125;" data-testid="permalink_stream_story" id="u_0_u"><div class="_3ccb" data-gt="&#123;&quot;type&quot;:&quot;click2canvas&quot;,&quot;fbsource&quot;:703,&quot;ref&quot;:&quot;nf_generic&quot;&#125;" id="u_0_v"><div></div><div class="userContentWrapper _5pcr" role="article" aria-label="Story"><div class="_1dwg"><div class="_4r_y"><div class="_6a uiPopover _5pbi _5puc _5v56 _b1e" id="u_0_w" data-ft="&#123;&quot;tn&quot;:&quot;V&quot;&#125;"><a class="_5pbj _p" aria-label="Story options" href="#" aria-haspopup="true" aria-expanded="false" rel="toggle" role="button" id="u_0_x"></a></div></div><div class="_4gns accessible_elem"></div><div class="clearfix _5x46"><a class="_5pb8 _29h _303" href="https://www.facebook.com/john.gfoeller?fref=nf" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1" data-ft="&#123;&quot;tn&quot;:&quot;m&quot;&#125;" data-hovercard="/ajax/hovercard/user.php?id=1057046668"><div class="_38vo"><img class="_s0 _5xib _5sq7 _44ma _rw img" src="https://scontent-sjc2-1.xx.fbcdn.net/hprofile-xap1/v/t1.0-1/c32.6.662.662/s50x50/1491771_10207361549571099_4244919816644257362_n.jpg?oh=61d492b7a3c493de903a4f509df70c04&amp;oe=5714B851" alt="" /></div></a><div class="_3dp _29k"><div><div class="_6a"><div class="_6a _6b" style="height:40px"></div><div class="_6a _6b"><h5 class="_5pbw" data-ft="&#123;&quot;tn&quot;:&quot;C&quot;&#125;"><span class="fwn fcg"><span class="fwb fcg" data-ft="&#123;&quot;tn&quot;:&quot;;&quot;&#125;"><span aria-hidden="true">‎</span><a href="https://www.facebook.com/john.gfoeller?fref=nf" data-hovercard="/ajax/hovercard/user.php?id=1057046668&amp;extragetparams=%7B%22fref%22%3A%22nf%22%2C%22directed_target_id%22%3A73203208283%7D">John Gfoeller<a href="https://www.facebook.com/john.gfoeller?fref=nf"></a></a><span aria-hidden="true">‎</span><span class="accessible_elem">&nbsp;</span><i class="mhs img sp_fWWiuJgc8JM sx_ad3c90"><u>to</u></i><span class="accessible_elem">&nbsp;</span><a class="_wpv" href="/groups/ProgressiveOrthodoxChristianity/?fref=nf" data-hovercard="/ajax/hovercard/group.php?id=73203208283&amp;extragetparams=%7B%22fref%22%3A%22nf%22%7D">Progressive Orthodox Christianity<a href="/groups/ProgressiveOrthodoxChristianity/?fref=nf"></a></a></span></span></h5><div class=""><div class="_5pcp"><span><span class="fsm fwn fcg"><a class="_5pcq" href="/groups/ProgressiveOrthodoxChristianity/permalink/10153398713383284/" target=""><abbr title="Tuesday, January 5, 2016 at 10:47pm" data-utime="1452055626" data-shorten="1" class="_5ptz timestamp livetimestamp"><span class="timestampContent">17 hrs</span></abbr></a></span></span><span role="presentation" aria-hidden="true"> · </span><div class="_6a _29ee _4f-9 _43_1" data-hover="tooltip" aria-label="Shared with: Public"><span><i class="_1lbg img sp_mySF3gA_MG- sx_9644b6"></i></span></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="_5pbx userContent" data-ft="&#123;&quot;tn&quot;:&quot;K&quot;&#125;"><p>Provenance:  </p><p> Theophany / the Baptism of Jesus Christ in the Jordan River. Icon in etched copper plates and gold filling. (See below for a description.)  It was made in Russia: perhaps circa the 1200s A.D., perhaps in the city of Old Riazan (where it was found in the ruins).  Now it is in the State Historical Museum, Moscow, Russia.</p><p> ++++++++++ </p><p> Description:  </p><p> The icon depicts the Baptism of Jesus Christ.  On the far left is a crowd of on-lookers.  In the center-left is St. John the Baptist.  He is baptizing his cousin, Jesus Christ, who is in the center.  Above Jesus and at the top of the icon, there is a semi-circle.  That is called a “mandorla.”  In Orthodox iconography, a mandorla is an artistic device to indicate the presence of God and things which can only be known by faith.  In this icon, the mandorla represents God the Father.  At the Baptism of Jesus Christ, the heavens parted and the Voice of God the Father said: “This is My beloved Son, with whom I am well-pleased.”  Immediately below that, there is a ray; and in the ray, there is the figure of a dove.  This represents the Holy Spirit, which came upon Jesus at His Baptism in the form of a dove.  Thus the three great lessons of Theophany are shown.  (1) It was the first public revelation of the divine nature of Jesus Christ.  (2) It was the first public revelation of the Trinity.  (3) By inference, it was the first revelationof the Trinity’s own eternal life of light and love which God offers to share with us in Jesus Christ: now and forever.  To the right of Jesus Christ, there are two angels (one with a towel to dry Him off).  Their presence is not recorded in the Bible, but they are added for two reasons.  They show reverence for Christ.  Also, the presence of the three angels recalls the foreshadowing of the revelation of the Trinity in the Old Testament: when the three angels visited Abraham by the Oak Tree at Mamre. (Genesis 13:18, Genesis 18:1-16)  The river stands for the Jordan River, and the fish stand for the creatures and all the waters who were blessed and cleansed by Christ at His Theophany: because God in Jesus Christ is renewing and cleansing all of His creation.  (See Psalm 114:3,7 / Psalm 113:3,7 in the Septuagint for a foreshadowing of this.)  Note the presence of the Cross in the river in this icon; the cleansing of Creation by Jesus Christ was finished (“It is accomplished.” John 19:30) by His Cross and Resurrection.  </p><p> The artistic technique of this icon is worthy of attention.  It is made of a copper plate with a dark varnish and gold gilding.  In this technique, copper plates were covered with a varnish, then they were etched with the design, then they were washed in acid.  Then the etching was painted with a gold-mercury amalgam.  Then it was heated.  The mercury would evaporate, leaving the gold behind in the etching to create the design of gold on a dark blue background.  The copper plates were thus transformed into beautiful, durable icons that could be mounted to a variety of surfaces (like the front doors of churches).  It was a common form of iconography in Byzantium and Russia.  </p><p> A magnificent example of this technique survives in the “golden gates” / the bronze doors of the Cathedral of the Nativity of St. Mary the Theotkos at uzdal, Russia (near Moscow).  For photographs of these gold-inlayed-bronze icons of Suzdal, see <a href="http://l.facebook.com/l.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.temples.ru%2Fshow_picture.php%3FPictureID%3D155056&amp;h=6AQHoDa0GAQHZxYfyXwdEJglWm5HigusjSrawm0d675yjcg&amp;enc=AZMyXie5SlT6AbXVFGWFRbZ2KGWko5_5jqTRzp4Gp3lT8EJf34_ottCRMQXlEOm9yCtx7G4PVDePlay36kuCABemgS9Ci5EqZFyekjP-mgHW8VZfQj0NZfdog8k2JCsOpF6hlWJ8idNMs8JR_h5kXeYBTTqoGpvLI18TzS3W8CZj6rpvWLNgOBj6YetrKDLTwz8&amp;s=1" target="_blank" rel="nofollow" onmouseover="LinkshimAsyncLink.swap(this, &quot;http:\\/\\/www.temples.ru\\/show_picture.php?PictureID=155056&quot;);" onclick="LinkshimAsyncLink.referrer_log(this, &quot;http:\\/\\/www.temples.ru\\/show_picture.php?PictureID=155056&quot;, &quot;\\/si\\/ajax\\/l\\/render_linkshim_log\\/?u=http\\u00253A\\u00252F\\u00252Fwww.temples.ru\\u00252Fshow_picture.php\\u00253FPictureID\\u00253D155056&amp;h=6AQHoDa0GAQHZxYfyXwdEJglWm5HigusjSrawm0d675yjcg&amp;render_verification=0&amp;enc=AZMyXie5SlT6AbXVFGWFRbZ2KGWko5_5jqTRzp4Gp3lT8EJf34_ottCRMQXlEOm9yCtx7G4PVDePlay36kuCABemgS9Ci5EqZFyekjP-mgHW8VZfQj0NZfdog8k2JCsOpF6hlWJ8idNMs8JR_h5kXeYBTTqoGpvLI18TzS3W8CZj6rpvWLNgOBj6YetrKDLTwz8&amp;d&quot;);">http://www.temples.ru/show_picture.php?PictureID=155056</a>.  For a Google search for more photographs of the gold-inlayed bronze icons of Suzdal, see <a href="https://www.facebook.com/l.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com%2Fsearch%3Fq%3Dbronze%2Bgates%2Bicons%2Bsuzdal%26rlz%3D1C1NWPB_enUS577US577%26tbm%3Disch%26tbo%3Du%26source%3Duni